Background¶

For this data analysis, you will again analyze the currency exchange data but to a greater extent and including two different currencies for comparison. File DailyCurrencyData.csv contains the daily exchange rate of USD/JPY and USD/CNY from January 1999 through December 31st 2020. File MonthlyCurrencyData.csv contains the monthly exchange rate of USD/JPY and USD/CNY for the same time period. Similarly to homework 2, we will aggregate the daily data into weekly data. We will compare our analysis using ARMA modeling on both weekly and monthly data for the two currencies

Question 1. Weekly vs Monthly Exploratory Data Analysis (20 points)¶

1a. Based on your intuition, when would you use weekly instead of monthly time series data?

Response

Weekly data could be used if there is expected seasonality or trend on a weekly basis. By aggregating to monthly you could be reducing insights that might be available in the weekly data.

1b. Plot the time series plots for both currency exchange rates comparing weekly vs monthly data. How do the weekly and monthly time series data compare? How do the time series for the two currencies compare?

Response: Weekly vs Montly Time Series data comparison

In both CNY and JPY datasets the weekly data shows large variation whereas the monthly data is much smoother. This is expected by because the monthly data takes is a more agglomerated view of the weekly data which smoooths the data. We could see even more smoothing by agglomerating the monthly data to yearly.

# Vector of 1 to the length of weekly JPY data
points <- 1:length(weekly$JPY)

# Create splines model on weekly JPY data
gam.jpy.weekly <- gam(weekly$JPY ~ s(points))

# Fit data to splines model
gam.fit.jpy.weekly <- ts(fitted(gam.jpy.weekly), start = 2010, frequency = 52)

#Plot Weekly

Response: Exploratory Analysis of 1st Order Difference Data

The ACF plot of all first order differences show a weekly stationarity process. The ACF function rarely shows any large negative or positive peaks although there does seem to be some serial dependence in the CNY plots. As expected, the trend is reduced through differencing

In the weekly data, inflection points can be seen at the following lags (0.25, 0.75, 1, 1.5, 2, 2.5, 3). There does seem to be some cyclical pattern to the ACF plot.

In the monthly data inflection points can be seen at roughtly the same lags indicating that aggregating the data did not eliminate the potentail seasonality in the data.

For both currency exchange rates and using the training datasets, use the iterative model to fit an ARIMA(p,d,q) model with max AR and MA orders of 8, and a differencing order of 1 or 2. Display the summary of the final model fit. Compare statistical significance of the coefficients. Would a lower order model be suggested based on the statistical significance of the coefficients?

Analyzing weekly data with ARIMA model fitting

In [8]:
options(warn = -1)
weekly.train = head(weekly, n=length(weekly$Date)-8)
weekly.test = tail(weekly, n=8)

norderpq = 8
norderd = 2


p = c(1:norderpq)-1; q = c(1:norderpq)-1; d = c(1:norderd)

aic1 = matrix(0, norderpq, norderpq)
aic2 = matrix(0, norderpq, norderpq)

for (i in 1:norderpq){
    for (j in 1:norderpq){
        for (k in 1:norderd){
            modijk = arima(weekly.test$JPY, order = c(p[i], d[k], q[j]), method = 'ML')
            if (k == 1){
                aic1[i,j] = modijk$aic-2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)+2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)*length(weekly.train)/(length(weekly.train)-p[i]-q[j]-2)
            } else {
                aic2[i,j] = modijk$aic-2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)+2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)*length(weekly.train)/(length(weekly.train)-p[i]-q[j]-2)
            }
        }
    }
}

aicv1 = as.vector(aic1)
indexp1 = rep(c(1:norderpq),norderpq)
indexq1 = rep(c(1:norderpq),each=norderpq)
indexaic1 = which(aicv1 == min(aicv1))
porder1 = indexp1[indexaic1]-1
qorder1 = indexq1[indexaic1]-1

minaic1 = aic1[porder1+1,qorder1+1]

aicv2 = as.vector(aic2)
indexp2 = rep(c(1:norderpq),norderpq)
indexq2 = rep(c(1:norderpq),each=norderpq)
indexaic2 = which(aicv2 == min(aicv2))
porder2 = indexp2[indexaic2]-1
qorder2 = indexq2[indexaic2]-1

minaic2 = aic1[porder2+1,qorder2+1]

if (minaic1 < minaic2){
    final_model_jp = arima(weekly.train$JPY, order = c(porder1, 1, qorder1), method = 'ML')
    porderjp = porder1
    qorderjp = qorder1
} else {
    final_model_jp = arima(weekly.train$JPY, order = c(porder2, 2, qorder2), method = 'ML')
    porderjp = porder2
    qorderjp = qorder2
}

Response: Analysis of the ARIMA Fit for the Weekly Data

The model fit of the JPY model shows higher accuracy metrics than the CNY model. This is exhibited by the MAPE value that is higher in the final JPY model compared to CNY.

This is likely due to the heteroskedacitity in the later portion of the CNY dataset. The model fit may be improved by performing the log or box-cox transformation to reduce the unconstant variance.

## p-value function for the z-test taking as input the test statistic
pvalue.coef <- function(tv) {
  2 * (1 - pnorm(abs(tv)))
}

## Sample Code to compute the test statistics
tv.jpy.weekly <-as.numeric(final_model_jp$coef)/as.numeric(sqrt(diag(final_model_jp$var.coef)))
tv.cny.weekly <-as.numeric(final_model_cn$coef)/as.numeric(sqrt(diag(final_model_cn$var.coef)))

## Apply the pvalue.coef function
pvalues.jpy.weekly <- sapply(tv.jpy.weekly, pvalue.coef)
pvalues.cny.weekly <- sapply(tv.cny.weekly, pvalue.coef)

Response: Statistical Significance

All coffecients are not statistically signficant. There are more stastically significant coefficents in the JPY model than the CNY model. These models were not chosen based on the statistical significance of the coefficients. A lower order model may be recommended in the CNY model where the majority of the coefficients are insignificant. We can compare all AIC values across all the models tested to ensure the AIC of the chosen model is not significantly lower than the lower order models.

Response: Residual Analysis

JPY

The residual analysis of the final fitted model for the JPY dataset is shown above. The residuals are randomly scattered amongst 0 and do not display heterosketerdasicity. The variance of the residuals is stable over time. Further the autocorrelation function remains low in both the PACF and ACF indicating that seasonality and trend are well captured in the final model.

The hypothesis testing using the box-pierce and box-ljung methods return p-values greater than 0.05. This indicates that we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the data is not serially correlated.

CNY

The residual analysis of the final fitted model for the CNY dataset is shown above. The residuals show heteroskedasicity over the time period indicating the predicted value may deviate from the observed value more at the later time period. This observation is supported by the ACF and PACF plots where the autocorrelation function is larger at higher order lags. The spikes observed are just outside the confidence interval so it should be monitored going forward. There is not adequete evidence to show that the model is not a good fit to the data.

The hypothesis testing using the box-pierce and box-ljung methods return p-values greater than 0.05. This indicates that we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the data is not serially correlated.

Response: Prediction Accuracy

I can visually see that all observations are within the prediction bands.

The first observation when comparing prediction accuracy is that the scale of the two datasets is significantly different. Therefore, the accuracy metric cannot depend on scale. This is true of both MAPE and PM so either can be chosen. The lower prediction error of JPY indicates that this model is more accurate. The MAPE measure shows that both models do a good job at predicting the next 8 week currency exchange rates.

Another observation is that the first 3 predictions in the CNY dataset are close to the observed values. However, the predictions deviate more after this point. This is expected because the confidence interval increases at timepoints further from the historical data.

monthly.train = head(monthly, n=length(monthly$Date)-2)
monthly.test = tail(monthly, n=2)

norderpq = 8
norderd = 2


p = c(1:norderpq)-1; q = c(1:norderpq)-1; d = c(1:norderd)

aic1 = matrix(0, norderpq, norderpq)
aic2 = matrix(0, norderpq, norderpq)

for (i in 1:norderpq){
    for (j in 1:norderpq){
        for (k in 1:norderd){
            modijk = arima(monthly.train$JPY, order = c(p[i], d[k], q[j]), method = 'ML')
            if (k == 1){
                aic1[i,j] = modijk$aic-2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)+2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)*length(monthly.train)/(length(monthly.train)-p[i]-q[j]-2)
            } else {
                aic2[i,j] = modijk$aic-2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)+2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)*length(monthly.train)/(length(monthly.train)-p[i]-q[j]-2)
            }
        }
    }
}

aicv1 = as.vector(aic1)
indexp1 = rep(c(1:norderpq),norderpq)
indexq1 = rep(c(1:norderpq),each=norderpq)
indexaic1 = which(aicv1 == min(aicv1))
porder1 = indexp1[indexaic1]-1
qorder1 = indexq1[indexaic1]-1

minaic1 = aic1[porder1+1,qorder1+1]

aicv2 = as.vector(aic2)
indexp2 = rep(c(1:norderpq),norderpq)
indexq2 = rep(c(1:norderpq),each=norderpq)
indexaic2 = which(aicv2 == min(aicv2))
porder2 = indexp2[indexaic2]-1
qorder2 = indexq2[indexaic2]-1

minaic2 = aic1[porder2+1,qorder2+1]

if (minaic1 < minaic2){
    final_model_jp_monthly = arima(monthly.train$JPY, order = c(porder1, 1, qorder1), method = 'ML')
    porderjpmonthly = porder1
    qorderjpmonthly = qorder1
} else {
    final_model_jp_monthly = arima(monthly.train$JPY, order = c(porder2, 2, qorder2), method = 'ML')
    porderjpmonthly = porder2
    qorderjpmonthly = qorder2
}

The graphs above show the weekly and monthly predictions on the same plots for the JPY and CNY datasets.

Question 5. Reflection on ARIMA (5 points)¶

Considering your understanding of the ARIMA model in general as well as what your understanding of the behavior of the currency exchange data based on the completion of the above questions, how would you personally regard the effectiveness of ARIMA modelling? Where would it be appropriate to use it for forecasting and where would you recommend against? What are some specific points of caution one would need to consider when considering using it?

Response: Reflection on ARIMA

The ARIMA model was effective at modelling each exchange rate but could be improved. This is because of the following

  • Each dataset exhibited trend that was removed by differencing. By allowing differencing (d=1 in the ARIMA model), trend was removed and the the dataset exhibited weekly stationary behavior. This enabled a more accurate model by establishing constant mean and variance.
  • The ACF plots of the differenced data does show some cyclical pattern indicating seasonality may be present. A SARIMA model should be explored to see if it improves the fit.
  • The forecasting was appropriate when the number of forecasted data points is enough to generate an understanding of the forecast accuracy. Testing the forecast for only the next two months was not enough to understand if the forecast was accurate.
  • Points of caution: (1) The confidence interval increases dramatically at time points further into the future. It would be benefitial to refit an arima at each future timepoint should the application allow. (2) It is difficult to gauge a models accuracy with only a small number of test points. The data should be split enough to allow an adequete test dataset. (3) The dataset did exhibit some seasonality as evidenced by differenced data ACF plot. A SARIMA model would account for this seasonality and likely improve the forecasting power of the model.
